Override Methods & Memory (Quick Notes)

Based on: Override Methods & Inheritance

== vs .equals()

==

Compares memory locations (references).

.equals()

Compares object contents (if overridden).

Never use:

string1 == string2

Use:

string1.equals(string2)
Object Equality

Default equals() comes from Object.

Without overriding:

equals()

behaves like

==

It checks if both variables point to the same object.

Override equals()

If you override:

equals()

You must also override

hashCode()

to maintain Java's contract.

hashCode()

Objects that are equal must have the same hash code.

IDE can auto-generate:

equals()
hashCode()
